<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-736-739  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 736 739.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC User  Dec 19 1990 n148 p16(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT EMAP Business andamp; Computer Publications(England) 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Jobs slashed as Rodime pulls manufacturing out of Scotland.andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Rodime Inc. (Management).andO;Topic:     Strategic PlanningLayoffReorganizationForeign ManufactureScotlandDisk Drives.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Jobs slashed as Rodime pulls manufacturing out of Scotland Rodime, the diskdrive maker, is withdrawing its manufacturing from its base in Scotland, inorder to stem losses.andM;All production will be transferred to a plant which the company currentlyuses in Singapore, with the exception of the new 120Mb 3 1/2-inch hard diskwhich is being developed jointly with Victor of Japan (see news, issue 146).andO;This will be produced in Japan.andM;Ninety of the 240 Rodime employees at Glenrothes, Scotland are said to belosing their jobs, although no Rodime spokesperson was available for comment.andM;Rodime managing director Peter Bailey has made it clear that he thinksrestructuring is necessary to bring the company back into profit, which ithas been denied for the last five years.andM;In the first nine months of this year, it made a loss of 5.8 million pounds,and was providing 2.8 million pounds to finance the changes during the lastquarter.andP;  The company's fourth quarter ended on 30 September 1990 and theresults for that quarter will be announced next month.andM;Manufacturing will stop at Glenrothes at the end of January, and the sitewill continue to house the main design and product engineering centre.andP;  Itwill also handle all repair work.andM;According to reports, the company will continue with its plans to develop anautomated production line in Glenrothes, which will give it the advantage ofremaining within the single European market.andM;The company's profitability received a boost last month when IBM unexpectedlysettled a patent dispute in Rodime's favour.andM;It negotiated a &quot;considerable&quot; payment, according to Dr Norman White,Rodime's chief technical officer.andP;  IBM is thought to have paid out about 10.3million pounds.andO;</TEXT></DOC>